<Layout title="Section 9 – Elimination">
  <h1>Section 9: Elimination</h1>
  <p><em>Competency 7093.4.9 – Performs Elimination Requirements</em></p>
  <p>
    Perform skills for patients with elimination problems (urinary catheter care, enemas,
    ostomy care) and prepare a comprehensive care plan.
  </p>

  <h2>Urinary Elimination</h2>
  <h3>Normal Urinary Patterns</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Normal output: ≥ 0.5 mL/kg/hr or ≥ 30 mL/hr; report output &lt; 30 mL/hr for &gt; 2 consecutive hours.</li>
    <li>Normal color: pale to medium yellow (amber); dark urine may indicate dehydration.</li>
    <li>Normal frequency: 6–8 voids per day.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Urinary Incontinence Types</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Type</th><th>Description</th><th>Nursing Intervention</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Stress</td><td>Leakage with increased abdominal pressure (coughing, sneezing)</td><td>Pelvic floor (Kegel) exercises</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Urge</td><td>Sudden strong urge; inability to delay voiding</td><td>Bladder training; scheduled toileting</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Overflow</td><td>Bladder unable to empty; dribbling overflow</td><td>Catheterization; treat underlying cause</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Functional</td><td>Physical or cognitive barrier to reaching toilet in time</td><td>Bedside commode; prompted voiding</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Reflex</td><td>No sensation of need to void; occurs reflexively</td><td>Timed voiding; intermittent catheterization</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Urinary Catheterization</h2>
  <div class="warning">
    <strong>⚠️ CAUTI Prevention</strong>
    Catheter-associated urinary tract infection (CAUTI) is the most common HAI. Insert
    catheters only when necessary; remove as soon as possible.
  </div>
  <ul>
    <li>Use strict sterile technique for indwelling catheter insertion.</li>
    <li>Maintain a closed drainage system; keep drainage bag below bladder level.</li>
    <li>Secure catheter to inner thigh (female) or upper thigh/abdomen (male) to prevent traction.</li>
    <li>Perform catheter care twice daily and after each bowel movement.</li>
    <li>Never allow the drainage bag to touch the floor; empty when ½–¾ full.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Types of Urinary Catheters</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Intermittent straight catheter:</strong> Inserted to drain bladder, then removed.</li>
    <li><strong>Indwelling (Foley) catheter:</strong> Left in place; balloon inflated in bladder.</li>
    <li><strong>Suprapubic catheter:</strong> Inserted through abdominal wall into bladder; used long-term.</li>
    <li><strong>External male catheter (condom catheter):</strong> Non-invasive option for male patients.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Bowel Elimination</h2>
  <h3>Normal Bowel Patterns</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Normal frequency: 3 times/day to 3 times/week.</li>
    <li>Bristol Stool Chart: Type 3–4 is ideal (sausage-shaped, smooth).</li>
    <li>Factors affecting elimination: diet, fluid intake, activity, medications (opioids cause constipation), emotional status.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Common Bowel Problems</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Problem</th><th>Definition</th><th>Key Interventions</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Constipation</td><td>&lt; 3 stools/week; hard, difficult to pass</td><td>Increase fiber/fluids; ambulation; stool softeners</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Diarrhea</td><td>Loose, watery stools &gt; 3/day</td><td>Identify cause; fluid/electrolyte replacement; skin protection</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Fecal impaction</td><td>Hard stool mass in rectum unable to pass</td><td>Digital removal (per order); enema; disimpaction</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Fecal incontinence</td><td>Involuntary passage of stool</td><td>Bowel training; skin integrity protection; fecal management system</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Enemas</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Position patient in left Sims' position (left lateral with right knee flexed) to follow bowel anatomy.</li>
    <li>Lubricate rectal tube; insert 3–4 inches in adults; 2–3 inches in children.</li>
    <li>Administer solution slowly; stop if cramping is severe; hold for 5–10 minutes before expelling.</li>
    <li>Types: cleansing (large-volume tap water or soapsuds), retention (oil-retention for impaction), commercially prepared (e.g., Fleet).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Ostomy Care</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Colostomy:</strong> Opening from colon; stool consistency varies by location (firmer = more distal).</li>
    <li><strong>Ileostomy:</strong> Opening from ileum; liquid to semi-liquid stool; higher electrolyte loss risk.</li>
    <li>Assess stoma: should be moist, pink/red, and slightly raised. Report dark/black, dry, or retracted stoma immediately.</li>
    <li>Change pouch when 1/3 to 1/2 full; measure stoma each time for correct fit.</li>
    <li>Protect peristomal skin with barrier paste or powder.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Essential Lessons (Sherpath – Chapters 46, 47, 12)</h3>
